Agaricaceae Agaricus sp. Chocolate-Brown / Purple-Brown Brown Chocolate-Brown Ground Ground | Various. Roadsides, Grass, Meadows, Woodland... etc. Saprobic Medium Fibrous Fibrous / Scaly / None | Glabrous or with flattened fibers, not brightly coloured. Fleshy Yes Free / Barely Attached | Remote from stem. Pink when young. Dark brown and free or almost free at maturity. Close / Crowded Free Hollow Hollow / None | n/a Medium / Large | Veil: Yes | Flesh thick, white. Usually white / gray / brown. Flesh, cap margin, base of stipe can often bruise yellow / red. Agrocybe are smaller and don't always have a partial veil. Chemical Reactions: KOH- negative or yellow-orange Agaricus bitorquis, Agaricus arvensis, Agaricus campestris, Agaricus nanaugustus, Agaricus xanthodermus Contains many species. Some are easy, some are extremely difficult.

Bolbitiaceae Pholiotina sp. Rusty-brown Other Rusty-brown Wood Wood | In woody debris Saprobic Small Striate Striate / Wrinkled / None | Dry. Sometimes with a central bump. Thin, bald. Can be finley wrinkled in the center. Dark orange-brown centrally and yellow-brown towards the edge. Margin finely lined. Yes Attached / Barely Attached / Notched | Close, short gills frequent. Whitish becoming brownish. Attached None None | Brownish below, whitish above. Fragile, slightly swollen base. Lightly spotted white. Small | Veil: Yes / No | n/a Best recognized by terrestrial habitat, and persistent pale ring. Galerina is similar, but slightly larger, and grows on wood. Can be confused with other LBMs such as Conocybe, Agrocybe, or Tubaria species. NaN Pholiotina rugosa Only species for this genus in North East is P. rugosa

Saprobic probably Small Depressed Depressed / Striate / None | Blocky or squarish at first, then convex with possible sunken center, striate. Tacky when fresh but soon dry. Bald. Orange with a whitish margin when young, soon yellowish orange overall with a darker orange center No Decurrent | Running deeply down stem. Distant. Creamy or very pale orange. Decurrent None None | Dry, bald, coloured like cap. Basal mycelium white. Small | Veil: No | Minutely fibrillose throughout Lots of look alikes. Growing in moss will separate from Xeromphalina kauffmanii and Xeromphalina campanella, which grow in dense clusters on hardwood. Usually a bit larger: Cantharellus minor and Hygrocybe cantharellus NaN Rickenella fibula Only species of its genus, but difficult due to many small and simliar mushrooms.

When Limacella is dried up it can look like Lepiota family. Closely related to amanita, but not easily confused. NaN Limacella glischra, Limacella illinita NaN

Tricholomataceae Catathelasma sp. White Pale White Ground Ground | Under conifers, alone or scattered. Mycorrhizal Large Fibrous Fibrous / None | Whitish cap that develops grayish fibrils and spots. Yes Decurrent / Bluntly Attached | Whitish Decurrent Volva Volva / Rooting / None | Often swollen in the middle, somewhat rooting. Large | Veil: Yes | Tough. Ring prominant and double. Odor and taste are mild or slightly unpleasant. Not mealy. Flesh is white and hard. Tricholoma caligatum group do not have decurrent gills, no double ring, and are sometimes under hardwoods. Tricholoma murrillianum group are similar, but whiter and have a spicy odor. NaN Catathelasma ventricosum The only species found in the North East is C. ventricosum
